ion" did not prove to be the happy ending touted by official rhetoric. Instead of a "honeymoon," the Allied-Italian encounter in cities such as Naples and Rome appeared to be a lurid affair, where the black market reigned supreme and prostitution was the norm. Informed by the historical context as well as by their respective traditions, these texts become more than mirrors of the encounter or generic allegories. Instead, they are sites in which to explore repressed traumas that inform how the occupation unfolded and is remembered, including the Holocaust, the American Civil War, and European colonialism, as well as individual traumatic events like the massacre of the Fosse Ardeatine and the mass civilian rape near Rome by colonial soldiers  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xLiterature and the war. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xMotion pictures and the war. 4aAllied occupation of Italy. 4aNaples in literature. 4aRome in literature. 4aWorld War II. 4amilitary occupation. 4aprostitution in literature. 4athe Holocaust in literature. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War II.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311071028140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823284528zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823284528423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823284528.jpg  a978-3-11-071028-1  NYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK